"Abstract One very active area of high technology law practice — protection and licensing of “volatile” electronic market data — is sited on the intersection of several legal issues, of which some are: Is a single datum, if embodied in a program, which contains instructions to treat the datum as text, as well as the text of the datum itself, protected by copyright? Is it sufficiently substantial? It is sufficiently original? If so, is that originality a characteristoc of a program or of the literary work in electronic form generated by a program? Is each single electronic trading datum to be regarded as generated by a human being, or by a computer? Every datum generated in an electronic (or any other) form traditionally is protected by exchanges' confidentiality agreements: as a matter of public policy, is this situation under threat of change? If single data are the subject of intellectual property rights (IPRs) then (matters of public policy concerning barriers to market access aside) will the apparent current drift of EC competition law policy, as exemplified by the ‘Magill’ cases, act so as to limit the IPR owners' rights? It is intended in this article to describe the industrial context, to set out some details of current data licensing practice, and perhaps to open a debate. Currently data sources and distributors are erring on the side of caution and treating their electronic trading data as if each individual datum is copyright protectable. Buyers of these volatile data are seeking from the sources and distributors licenses for use which incorporate standard form warranties and indemnification. Is this the appropriate legal mechanism controlling and getting revenue for trading data?"
